Compile/run:
     - Compile using
            make MetroSim
     - run executable with
            ./MetroSim stationsFile passFile [commands]
     - Run with a command file:
            ./MetroSim stations.txt output.txt commands.txt
     - Save stdout for diff:
            ./MetroSim stations.txt outputFile.txt < test_commands.txt >
            my.output
            ./the_MetroSim stations.txt outputFile.txt < test_commands.txt 
            > ref.output
            diff ref.output my.output
     - Feed commands via stdin:
            ./MetroSim stations.txt output.txt < commands.txt


Program Purpose:
MetroSim is a small train simulator. It reads station names, then
processes simple commands to add riders, move the train, unload riders
at their stop, and log exits. After each command it prints the full
state like who is on the train, and who is waiting at each station.


Acknowledgements: Used ideas from the CS15 lab and lecture. 


Files: 

Passenger.cpp: Implementation of the Passenger class

Passenger.h: Interface of the Passenger class with id, start station, end
station, and print.

PassengerQueue.h: Interface of the PassengerQueue class with FIFO queue of
Passenger with front, enqueue, dequeue, size, and print.

PassengerQueue.cpp: Implementation of PassengerQueue using std::list;
supports enqueue/dequeue/front/size/print and throws on empty front/dequeue.

unit_tests.h: Tests for Passenger and PassengerQueue so far, checks
constructors, getters, print format, FIFO order, size updates, and
exceptions.

MetroSim.h:
Interface of the MetroSim class. Holds station names, one waiting
queue per station, train buckets by destination, the current
station index, and the next passenger id. Declares printing,
boarding, unloading, and the command loop.

MetroSim.cpp:
Implementation of MetroSim. Prints state, boards riders at the
current station, moves the train with wrap-around, unloads riders
at arrival (and logs them), and runs the command loop that reads
commands from a stream.

main.cpp:
Driver. Parses command-line args, opens files, reads station names,
builds MetroSim, prints the initial state, and runs the command
loop (from stdin or from a commands file). Writes exit logs to the
output file.

stations.txt:
     an example file containing a list of stations.

test_commands.txt:
     sample list of commands that you could give to the simulator

the_metroSim:
     reference implementation for students to see how 

commands.txt, commands2.txt, commands3.txt, commands4.txt:
Larger command scripts for more cases: multiple passengers,
wrap-around, consecutive moves, mixed spacing and blank lines.

orangeLine.txt:
A second station list (The Boston Orange line) to test that the program
works with any set of station names.


Data Structures:
Stations are stored in a vector of PassengerQueue. Each stations[i] is the 
waiting line at station i and follows FIFO order. The train keeps a vector
of PassengerQueue named trainByDest, where trainByDest[d] holds riders
whose destination is station d. This makes unloading easy on arrival
because we simply empty that one bucket. The simulator also tracks cur,
the index of the current station, and nextId, the next rider id. The
key rules are clear: a rider is either waiting at a station or 
riding in exactly one train bucket, never both. Moving the train means
add one to cur and wrap around using the number of stations N (cur + 1)
% N. At every stop we unload first and then board.

Architectural Overview: 
On start, main.cpp reads station names, creates MetroSim, prints the
initial state, then runs processCommands. The command loop reads one
line at a time. For "p A B" it creates a new Passenger with id
nextId and enqueues it at stations[A]. For "m m" it boards everyone
waiting at cur into the train buckets keyed by destination, advances
cur with wrap-around, unloads everyone whose destination is the new
cur (and logs each exit), then prints the state. For "m f" it prints
the goodbye message and exits. Any other or blank line simply prints
the current state again to match the demo’s feel. All printing follows
the format: first the train line, then each station with
"TRAIN:" in front of the current station line and spaces elsewhere.


Testing:

I tested in three ways. First, I wrote small unit tests for Passenger
and PassengerQueue to check constructors, getters, print format, FIFO
order, size changes, and the errors thrown when calling front or
dequeue on an empty queue. These tests ran fast and caught mistakes 
early. Second, I ran command scripts from files and captured stdout, 
then used diff with the reference run that used the same inputs. The 
scripts covered an empty start, a single rider, many riders to one stop, 
riders to many stops, boarding followed by moving, wrap around, and lines 
that have extra spaces or are blank. Third, I swapped the station list 
with orangeLine.txt to confirm the code does not depend on specific 
names. I also checked that exit logs follow “Passenger X left train 
at station NAME” and that riders only appear on the train between their 
start and end stations. I verified that queues never underflow by 
checking sizes before front or dequeue.


Part that you found most difficult:

Matching the exact print format (indentation, braces, spacing)
(aka passing diff) and keeping the order right at stops 
(unload before board) took the most care. Getting file I/O 
and command parsing to work with both stdin and a commands file 
was also a common source of small bugs early on.

Time Spent: I spent about 14 hours on this assignment. 
